<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-260-858  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 260 858.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  May 1 1989 n536 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Neural nose to sniff out explosives at JFK airport. (New York'sJFK International Airport)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Johnson, R. Colin.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) will install the firstneural network-based Thermal Neutron Analysis (TNA) bomb detectorat NY's JFK International Airport in May 89.andP;  The agency orderedsix of the TNA units from Science Applications International Corp,which develop the systems under an FAA Randamp;D contract.andP;  The FAA willdeploy the first six at international airports but will requireairlines to buy about 100 of the near-$1 million units fordomestic airports.andP;  The TNA system identifies explosive materialsby bombarding them with low-energy neutrons and identifying theresulting gamma-ray emissions.andP;  New materials can be easilylearned by inserting them into the TNA and commanding the systemto learn the materials' characteristics.andP;  The TNA can scan 10 bagsper minute with no human intervention.andP;  The system has beencertified safe for food, drugs, film, and magnetic media.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Science Applications International Corp. (product development).andO;Product:   Thermal Neutron Analysis (design and construction).andO;Topic:     System DesignNeural NetworksDetectorsAirportsFAAApplicationsDisaster PlanningJohn F. Kennedy International Airport.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>